                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d585">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.93/9–2846: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-09-28">September 28,
                            1946</date>.<lb/>[Received September 28—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1557. Wu Teh-chen, Secretary General [of] Kuomintang, told United Press in
                    commenting on Gromyko’s recent charges to Security Council, <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“American GI’s certainly don’t jeopardize world peace by remaining in
                            China, but on the contrary actually help bring about peace.…<note n="66"
                                xml:id="d585fn66">Omission indicated in the original.</note> I am of
                            the opinion world peace would be endangered only when foreign troops
                            enter the territory of another country and remain without sanction of
                            its government.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Official <hi rend="italic">Central Daily News</hi> editorial September 27 took
                    same stand as above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
